{
  "body" : "Create a high-finish historical biography poster titled \"3D Historical Breakout Biography Poster\" for {{person_name}} ({{person_role}}, {{era}}). This is NOT a generic history poster — it must follow this specific structure:\n\n  CENTRAL: full-body 3D historical figure with breakout action\n  SURROUNDING: light, floating, semi-transparent historical event clusters\n  BOTTOM: lightweight curatorial timeline\n  LEFT: large title block with calligraphic name + tags + tagline\n\n— Central figure (THE HERO — must be the dominant visual) —\nA COMPLETE FULL-BODY standing 3D portrait of {{person_name}}, rendered with strong volume, sculptural weight, monumental presence and historical aura. Costume, headwear, armor, ornaments, sash, footwear, accessories — all historically accurate to {{era}} and to the role of {{person_role}}. Realistic, weighty, cinematic-grade impact. Rendered as a museum-grade 3D character (think Naughty Dog / ArtStation hero-character level).\n\nStance: {{stance}}.\n\nUnder the figure's feet: a thin, elegant monumental pedestal — just enough to support the figure, NOT a heavy block that crushes the composition.\n\n— Breakout action (CRITICAL — non-negotiable) —\nThe figure must NOT simply stand passively. It must perform an unmistakable forward-breaking action through the picture plane. Specifically:\n{{key_prop}}\n\nThe forward-extended hand / arm / key prop must read with strong near-large / far-small perspective compression and clearly break OUT of the frame toward the viewer, producing a powerful 3D punch.\n\nABSOLUTELY CRITICAL: The forward-thrust key prop MUST be COMPLETELY visible and clearly identifiable. DO NOT crop the key prop down to a tiny stub. If the prop is a sword/spear, show its full blade or a substantial portion. If it is a scroll/decree, show enough of the unrolled section that the viewer can recognize the form. The whole point of the composition fails if this prop is mangled.\n\n— Surrounding event clusters (LIGHT, FLOATING, NOT HEAVY CARDS) —\nArrange {{events_count}} around the figure, distributed across the open space (top-left, top-right, mid-left, mid-right, lower-left, lower-right, etc.) at varying heights and depths. \n\nDO NOT render them as heavy, neat, evenly-spaced rectangular cards. Instead make them light, semi-transparent, multi-oriented, floating historical event clusters. Each cluster is composed of 2–4 sub-fragments containing:\n  • a small numeric index (01, 02, 03 ...)\n  • the year or year-range\n  • the event title (3–8 characters / 1–4 words)\n  • a brief 1–2 line description (small text — may be slightly simplified if model has trouble with dense text)\n  • a tiny historical scene illustration or icon (battle, court, scholar, scroll, mountain, etc.)\n  • thin gold connecting lines, open-edge frames, dot markers, annotation lines\n\nFeel: like a historical archive deconstructed into airy time-slices, floating around the figure — NOT business-style info cards.\n\nClusters must have varied orientations and spatial perspective: some tilt left, some tilt right, some rotate inward, some flip outward; some sit higher, some lower; with front/back layering. They MAY be slightly occluded by the figure's arm, robe edge, or weapon — this creates real spatial depth. Apply glass / acrylic feel, micro-glowing edges, incomplete borders, and slight dis-aligned overlapping layers. Information-rich but visually LIGHT. They must NEVER overpower the central figure.\n\n— Title block (LEFT side, vertical-stacked) —\nLarge title: \"{{person_name}}\" rendered in an Eastern historical typeface — calligraphic, stele-engraved, or ink-brush feel (for Chinese names use 楷书 / 隶书 / 行书 / 篆书 style). Beside or below it, in much smaller refined type:\n  • Era + lifespan: {{era}}\n  • Role tag: {{person_role}}\n  • Core keywords: {{core_keywords}}\n  • One-line tagline: \"{{subtitle_line}}\"\nKeep the title block calm, simple, restrained. NEVER overpack it.\n\n— Bottom timeline (THIN, ELEGANT, CURATORIAL) —\nA single slim horizontal timeline running across the bottom of the poster, connecting the major years of {{person_name}}'s life and corresponding to the surrounding event clusters. Style: museum exhibition guide line / curatorial scale / archival index — using thin gold lines, small dots, clean year numbers, small text annotations, and a few decorative nodes. \n\nDO NOT render the timeline as a heavy black bar or a giant info-block at the bottom. It is a thin breath of information, not a footer.\n\n— Background —\n{{background_texture}}. Overall low saturation, clean, restrained. May include faint map textures, ancient architecture silhouettes, document fragments, seals, gold connecting lines, annotation lines, dot markers, territorial outlines — establishing an airy, rational, archival exhibition atmosphere.\n\n— Color palette —\n{{color_scheme}}. Apply consistently to:\n  - figure's costume / armor as the dominant material color\n  - cluster glow edges and gold lines as the accent\n  - background paper as the neutral base\n\n— Typography —\nAll labels, descriptions, years and timeline text in {{label_language}}. Title in calligraphic / engraved style; everything else in clean, refined editorial type (sans-serif for English; 思源宋体 / 方正小标宋 / 楷体 for Chinese). Generous spacing, museum-publication discipline.\n\n— Composition contrast (CORE LAW of this poster) —\nMUST establish clear contrast:\n  • Central figure: HEAVY, real, three-dimensional, strong light & shadow, strong volume\n  • Surrounding event clusters: thin, transparent, floating, micro-glowing, refined, rational\n  • Figure's action: forward-breaking, frame-bursting, with spatial explosion\n  • Bottom timeline: light, restrained, only gathers information\n\n— Aspect ratio —\nCaptured in {{aspect_ratio}}.\n\n— Additional details —\n{{extra_notes}}\n\n— Priority order (if conflicts arise) —\n1. Central figure must be COMPLETE FULL-BODY\n2. Forward-thrust prop must be COMPLETELY VISIBLE with strong 3D impact\n3. Surrounding clusters must be LIGHT FLOATING, never heavy cards\n4. Central figure HEAVY, information system LIGHT — clear visual weight contrast\n5. Bottom timeline must stay LIGHT, clean, never crushing\n\nIf the model struggles with rendering large amounts of small text accurately, prioritize legibility of: the person's NAME, YEARS, INDEX NUMBERS, and EVENT TITLES. Brief descriptions may be visually simplified (faux-text bars or shortened phrases) to leave room for post-production typography.\n\n— Strictly avoid —\n- Do NOT crop the key prop to a tiny stub — show the full extended hand and the full prop\n- Do NOT render event clusters as opaque heavy rectangular business-card layouts\n- Do NOT make the surrounding clusters louder, brighter or larger than the central figure\n- Do NOT make the pedestal thick like a heavy block — it must be thin and elegant\n- Do NOT make the bottom timeline a heavy black bar or large footer block\n- Do NOT overpack the title area with stacked tags — keep it restrained\n- Do NOT generate gibberish characters in CJK text — prefer fewer correct words over many broken ones\n- Do NOT render the figure as cartoon, anime cel-shading, or stylized — this is photoreal cinematic 3D character art\n- Do NOT use rainbow / neon palette — stay within {{color_scheme}}\n- Do NOT add modern UI elements (rounded buttons, mobile mockups, progress bars)\n- Do NOT add extra signatures, watermarks, or modern brand logos (unless extra_notes specifies)\n\nKeywords: historical biography poster, 3D character, breakout composition, frame-breaking action, museum archive, floating event clusters, curatorial timeline, calligraphic title, cinematic, sculptural, monumental, editorial poster",
